  'f8d994ab-5263-4e87-b209-49ba57c2de0f',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$Kotlin Backend Concurrency — Coroutines Over Threads$escape$,
  $escape$Kotlin doesn't use OS threads for concurrency — it uses coroutines, lightweight suspending functions scheduled by a CoroutineDispatcher. On the backend (Ktor, Spring WebFlux with coroutines), you replace blocking I/O with `suspend` functions that yield execution without parking a thread. `Dispatchers.IO` backs blocking calls with a thread pool sized to 64 or `availableProcessors`, while `Dispatchers.Default` is CPU-bound. Structured concurrency via `coroutineScope {}` ensures child coroutines are cancelled if the parent fails — no orphaned work. Use `async {}` + `await()` for parallel decomposition: two DB queries run concurrently, and `awaitAll()` collects both. Channels replace shared mutable state for producer-consumer pipelines; `Flow<T>` handles cold streams with backpressure via `buffer()` and `conflate()`. Unlike Java's `CompletableFuture` chains, coroutines keep imperative control flow — exception handling is a plain `try/catch`. Under load, 10k concurrent requests stay on dozens of threads instead of thousands, which is the core JVM win.$escape$,
  $escape$import kotlinx.coroutines.*

suspend fun fetchUserAndOrders(userId: Long): UserDetail = coroutineScope {
    val user = async(Dispatchers.IO) { userRepo.findById(userId) }
    val orders = async(Dispatchers.IO) { orderRepo.findByUser(userId) }
    UserDetail(user.await(), orders.await())
}

// In Ktor route handler (already in coroutine scope)
get("/users/{id}") {
    val id = call.parameters["id"]!!.toLong()
    call.respond(fetchUserAndOrders(id))
}$escape$,
  $escape$kotlin$escape$,
