INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  '99c6bd89-11e8-4cb8-93bf-531147d99c70',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$Kotlin Backend Error Handling — Exceptions vs Result<T>, and When to Use Each$escape$,
  $escape$Kotlin gives you two first-class error handling strategies: exceptions and the `Result<T>` type. For I/O-heavy backend code (Ktor routes, repository calls, external APIs), exceptions are costly — they unwind the call stack, pollute coroutine scopes, and obscure control flow. Prefer `Result<T>` for expected failure paths.

Use `runCatching { }` to wrap any call that can fail and get back a `Result<T>`. Chain `.map {}`, `.recover {}`, and `.getOrElse {}` to propagate and transform errors without nesting try/catch blocks. For domain errors, define a sealed class hierarchy (`sealed class AppError`) and use `Result<T>` with a typed error via a custom `Either<E, A>` (Arrow's `Either` is idiomatic here).

Reserve exceptions for truly exceptional cases — programming errors, unrecoverable states, or third-party library contracts. In Ktor, install a `StatusPages` plugin to catch domain `AppError` types and map them to HTTP responses centrally, keeping route handlers clean. Coroutine cancellation still uses `CancellationException` — never catch it blindly with `catch (e: Exception)`.$escape$,
  $escape$sealed class AppError {
    data class NotFound(val id: String) : AppError()
    data class Unauthorized(val reason: String) : AppError()
}

suspend fun findUser(id: String): Result<User> = runCatching {
    db.users.findById(id) ?: throw NoSuchElementException(id)
}.mapCatching { it }
 .recover { e ->
     if (e is NoSuchElementException) throw AppError.NotFound(e.message ?: id)
     else throw e
 }

// In Ktor route:
get("/users/{id}") {
    findUser(call.parameters["id"]!!)
        .onSuccess { call.respond(it) }
        .onFailure { e -> call.respond(HttpStatusCode.NotFound, e.message) }
}$escape$,
  $escape$kotlin$escape$,
