INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  '0e0747c6-bf77-4a87-b8ef-f99c0948113f',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$Kotlin Backend Memory Management — JVM GC, Value Classes, and Heap Pressure$escape$,
  $escape$Kotlin on the JVM delegates memory management to the garbage collector — G1GC by default, ZGC or Shenandoah for low-latency workloads. Every class instance lands on the heap; primitives like `Int`, `Long`, and `Boolean` are stack-allocated only when the compiler can prove no boxing occurs. Boxing happens silently: `List<Int>` boxes every element into `java.lang.Integer`, while `IntArray` stays unboxed.

Kotlin's `value class` (formerly inline class) is the primary tool to reduce heap pressure. Wrapping a single primitive in a value class costs zero heap allocation at the call site — the JVM sees the raw type. This matters in hot paths: a `UserId(value: Long)` passed through a thousand-RPS endpoint creates no GC pressure.

Null safety is Kotlin's memory safety story. The compiler eliminates null-pointer paths statically, so you never dereference a null reference at runtime — unlike Java's unchecked NPEs. For backend services, pair `-XX:+UseZGC` with value classes on domain primitives to keep pause times under 1ms and object churn low.$escape$,
  $escape$// Unboxed domain primitive — zero heap allocation at call sites
@JvmInline
value class UserId(val value: Long)

@JvmInline
value class Email(val value: String)

data class User(val id: UserId, val email: Email)

fun findUser(id: UserId): User? {
    // UserId is erased to Long on JVM bytecode — no wrapper object
    return db.query("SELECT * FROM users WHERE id = ?", id.value)
        .mapOrNull { row -> User(UserId(row.getLong("id")), Email(row.getString("email"))) }
}$escape$,
  $escape$kotlin$escape$,
