INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  'f301ccb5-63ea-4807-812e-28d09938297d',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$Kotlin Backend Cold Starts — JVM JIT vs GraalVM Native Image$escape$,
  $escape$Kotlin compiles to JVM bytecode, not machine code. At runtime, HotSpot's JIT compiler profiles execution and recompiles hot paths into optimized native code — peak throughput is excellent, but you pay two costs: JVM initialization (~300–500ms) and JIT warm-up (first N invocations run interpreted). For a Ktor service on a container or AWS Lambda, cold start easily hits 2–4 seconds under load.

GraalVM Native Image flips the model: AOT compilation at build time produces a self-contained binary with no JVM bootstrap, cutting cold start to ~50ms. The trade-off is real — reflection, dynamic class loading, and Kotlin coroutine internals require explicit `reflect-config.json` hints, and you lose JIT's adaptive optimizations, so sustained throughput is lower.

For long-lived services (Kubernetes, Azure Container Apps), stay on JVM — JIT pays off. For serverless or scale-to-zero workloads, Ktor + `ktor-graalvm-native-image` plugin is the production answer. Micronaut Kotlin also ships with pre-built GraalVM metadata, reducing the reflection-config burden considerably.$escape$,
  $escape$// build.gradle.kts — Ktor + GraalVM Native Image
plugins {
    kotlin("jvm") version "2.0.21"
    id("io.ktor.plugin") version "3.0.3"
    id("org.graalvm.buildtools.native") version "0.10.3"
}

graalvmNative {
    binaries {
        named("main") {
            imageName.set("byteai-service")
            mainClass.set("com.byteai.ApplicationKt")
            buildArgs.add("--initialize-at-build-time=io.ktor,kotlinx.coroutines")
            buildArgs.add("-H:+ReportExceptionStackTraces")
        }
    }
}$escape$,
  $escape$kotlin$escape$,
