INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  'e15da754-2070-451e-b2ab-416adcab5ea6',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$Kotlin Backend Standard Library: What's Built In vs What You Still Need to Add$escape$,
  $escape$Kotlin's stdlib is powerful but deliberately lean. Scope functions (let, run, apply, also, with), collection transformations, and the Result<T> type for structured error handling are all built in — zero extra dependencies. The same goes for Sequence<T> for lazy pipelines, Regex, kotlin.math, kotlin.reflect, and string extensions like padStart, chunked, and windowed.

The sharp edge: kotlinx.coroutines — the async backbone of every Kotlin backend — is a separate artifact (org.jetbrains.kotlinx:kotlinx-coroutines-core). Don't assume it ships with the language. Same applies to kotlinx.serialization for JSON/CBOR encoding, kotlinx.datetime for platform-agnostic time APIs (java.time works on JVM but breaks in KMP), and Arrow for functional constructs like Either and Option.

For HTTP, the stdlib has nothing — use Ktor Client or OkHttp. Structured logging requires SLF4J + Logback or Log4j2. Dependency injection means Koin or Hilt or Spring.

The rule of thumb: kotlin.* is the language layer, kotlinx.* is the curated ecosystem, everything else is third-party. Confusing the three causes NoClassDefFoundError surprises on fresh deployments.$escape$,
  $escape$// ✅ stdlib — no extra deps (kotlin.*)
val result: Result<Int> = runCatching { "42".toInt() }
val doubled = listOf(1, 2, 3).map { it * 2 }.asSequence()
val name = "  kotlin  ".trim().replaceFirstChar { it.uppercase() }

// ⚠️ Needs: org.jetbrains.kotlinx:kotlinx-coroutines-core
import kotlinx.coroutines.*
val data = coroutineScope { async { fetchFromDb() }.await() }

// ⚠️ Needs: org.jetbrains.kotlinx:kotlinx-serialization-json
import kotlinx.serialization.json.Json
val json = Json.encodeToString(UserDto(id = 1, name = "Ada"))

// ⚠️ Needs: org.jetbrains.kotlinx:kotlinx-datetime
import kotlinx.datetime.Clock
val now = Clock.System.now()$escape$,
  $escape$kotlin$escape$,
