INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  '013d45c8-769b-4467-a511-50431f3c80b1',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$Kotlin BE — Coroutine Thread Model and What It Means for Horizontal Scaling$escape$,
  $escape$Kotlin's coroutine model fundamentally changes how you reason about horizontal scaling. Unlike Java's thread-per-request model (512KB–1MB stack each), Ktor handlers are suspend functions — they yield the underlying thread at suspension points rather than block it. A single `Dispatchers.Default` pool, sized to CPU cores, can multiplex thousands of concurrent requests.

When you add pod replicas, you're not fighting JVM thread exhaustion — each pod runs lean. The critical trap: bridging to blocking JDBC via `withContext(Dispatchers.IO)` is correct, but the IO dispatcher's default thread ceiling is 64 per process. Under horizontal scale, each replica carries its own pool, so database connection pressure multiplies linearly. Tune HikariCP's `maximumPoolSize` to actual per-pod connections, not global capacity.

For genuine non-blocking I/O, prefer `r2dbc` or Exposed's coroutine extension (`newSuspendedTransaction`) — these suspend the coroutine rather than park a thread, allowing each pod to absorb significantly more concurrent load before you need another replica. Stateless Ktor services with coroutine-native DB drivers are your lowest-cost horizontal scaling unit on the JVM.$escape$,
  $escape$fun Application.configureRouting(userRepo: UserRepository) {
    routing {
        get("/users/{id}") {
            val id = call.parameters["id"]?.toLong()
                ?: return@get call.respond(HttpStatusCode.BadRequest)
            // newSuspendedTransaction suspends the coroutine — no thread parked
            val user = newSuspendedTransaction(Dispatchers.IO) {
                userRepo.findById(id)
            }
            call.respond(user ?: HttpStatusCode.NotFound)
        }
    }
}$escape$,
  $escape$kotlin$escape$,
