INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  '22e6c7cf-c616-494c-b54e-5d08ee15ec13',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$Kotlin Backend Dev Tooling — REPL Scripts, Coroutine Debugger, and LSP Beyond IntelliJ$escape$,
  $escape$Kotlin's backend tooling has matured well outside IntelliJ's ecosystem. The `ki` shell (`brew install ki`) gives you a JVM-backed REPL that resolves classpath dependencies on-the-fly — useful for testing `kotlinx.serialization` mappings or coroutine behavior without spinning up a full Ktor or Spring Boot server.

For heavier prototyping, `.main.kts` files support `@file:DependsOn` to pull Gradle artifacts at runtime. Run them with `kotlinc -script probe.main.kts` to execute Ktor client calls or validate JSON deserialization logic as standalone scripts.

The coroutine debugger in IntelliJ (Settings → Build, Execution, Deployment → Kotlin → Coroutines → Enable coroutine agent) is Kotlin's most underused tool. It renders all suspended coroutines as a virtual thread tree, showing which dispatcher they're parked on and their full suspension stack trace — indispensable for diagnosing `Dispatchers.IO` pool exhaustion or structured concurrency scope leaks.

For LSP outside IntelliJ, `kotlin-language-server` (fwcd/kotlin-language-server) integrates with Neovim via `nvim-lspconfig` using `lspconfig.kotlin_language_server.setup{}` and with VS Code via the Kotlin extension. Point it at your Gradle project root; it resolves cross-module completions and go-to-definition after a one-time index.$escape$,
  $escape$// probe.main.kts — run with: kotlinc -script probe.main.kts
@file:DependsOn("io.ktor:ktor-client-core:2.3.12")
@file:DependsOn("io.ktor:ktor-client-cio:2.3.12")
@file:DependsOn("io.ktor:ktor-serialization-kotlinx-json:2.3.12")

import io.ktor.client.*
import io.ktor.client.engine.cio.*
import io.ktor.client.request.*
import io.ktor.client.statement.*
import kotlinx.coroutines.runBlocking

val client = HttpClient(CIO)
val body: String = runBlocking { client.get("https://httpbin.org/get").bodyAsText() }
println(body)
client.close()$escape$,
  $escape$kotlin$escape$,
